In mathematics, '''Boas–Buck polynomials''' are sequences of polynomials Φ{{su|b=''n''|p=(''r'')}}(''x'') given by [[generating function]]s of the form

:<math>\displaystyle C(zt^r B(t))=\sum_{n\ge0}\Phi_n^{(r)}(z)t^n</math>.

The case ''r''=1, sometimes called [[generalized Appell polynomials]], was studied by {{harvs|txt|last=Boas|authorlink=Ralph P. Boas, Jr.|last2=Buck|author2-link=Robert Creighton Buck|year=1958}}.

