{{Infobox scientist | name = Grigorii Mikhailovich Fichtenholz | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = FichtenholzPortrait.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date |1888|06|05}} | birth_place = [[Odessa]] | death_date = {{death date and age |1959|06|26 |1888|06|05}} | death_place = [[Leningrad]] | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Real analysis]], [[Functional analysis]] | workplaces = | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[Leningrad State University]] | thesis_title = Theory of Depending on Parameter Primary Definite Integrals | thesis_year = 1918 | doctoral_advisor = [[Samuil Shatunovsky]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = [[Leonid Kantorovich]], [[Isidor Natanson]] | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Grigorii Mikhailovich Fichtenholz''' (or '''Fikhtengolts''') ({{lang-ru|Григо́рий Миха́йлович Фихтенго́льц}}) (June 5, 1888 in [[Odessa]] &ndash; June 26, 1959 in [[Leningrad]]) was a Russian mathematician working on [[real analysis]] and [[functional analysis]]. Fichtenholz was one of the founders of the Leningrad school of real analysis.
He also authored a three-volume textbook 'Differential and Integral Calculus'. The books cover mathematical analysis of function of one real variable, functions of many real variables and of complex functions. Due to depth and precision of presentation of material, these books are defined as classical position in mathematical analysis. Book was translated, among others, into German, Chinese, and Persian however translation to English language has not been done still.
Fichtenholz's books about analysis are widely used in Middle and Eastern European as well as Chinese universities due to its exceptionality of detailed and well-ordered presentation of material about mathematical analysis. Due to unknown reasons, these books do not have the same fame in universities in other areas of the world.
He was an Invited Speaker of the [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM]] in 1924 in Toronto.<ref>{{cite book|author=Fichtenholz, Gr. M.|chapter=Sur la notion de fermeture des systèmes de fonctions|title=''In:'' Proceedings of the International Congress of Mathematicians in Toronto, August 11–16. 1924|volume=vol. 1|page=686|chapter-url=http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM1924.1/Main/icm1924.1.0686.0686.ocr.pdf}}</ref>
[[Leonid Kantorovich]] and [[Isidor Natanson]] were among his students.
