In [[mathematical logic]], a '''first-order Gödel logic''' is a member of a family of [[finite-valued logic|finite-]] or [[infinite-valued logic]]s in which the sets of [[truth value]]s ''V'' are closed subsets of the interval [0,1] containing both 0 and 1. Different such sets ''V'' in general determine different Gödel logics.  The concept is named after [[Kurt Gödel]].
<ref>
[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S016800720700019X First-order Gödel logics]
Authors: Matthias Baaz, Norbert Preining, Richard Zach.
</ref>

